<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="63" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,884,1269]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,919,944]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">Description.</emphasis>
Shell height to 
<quantity box="[542,633,920,944]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="22" pageNumber="63" unit="mm" value="2.8">2.8 mm</quantity>
(up to 
<quantity box="[728,799,920,944]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="63" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Melvill, J. C. &amp; Standen, R." box="[967,1257,919,944]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63" pagination="119 - 157" refId="ref17508" refString="Melvill, J. C. &amp; Standen, R. (1907) The marine Mollusca of the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, 46, 119 - 157, 1 pl." type="journal article" year="1907">Melvill &amp; Standen 1907</bibRefCitation>
); turritelliform, moderately solid. Protoconch large, of 1 markedly convex whorl; sculptured with 4 low, wide spiral cords. Teleoconch of up to 5.75 whorls, markedly convex in outline; last whorl comprising about 45% of total shell height. Suture impressed. Surface pale brownish, clearer at spiral sculpture; sculptured with 25 to 30 axial ribs per whorl and 4 spiral cords, the 2 adapical being stronger. Base delimited by a strong cord and sculptured with up to 9 additional, narrower cords. Aperture almost rounded, somewhat projected anteriorly, interior brownish with lighter margin; columellar callus narrow, slightly reflected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="63" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,884,1269]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1172,1197]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">Remarks.</emphasis>
The original figure by 
<bibRefCitation author="Melvill, J. C. &amp; Standen, R." box="[588,886,1172,1197]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63" pagination="119 - 157" refId="ref17508" refString="Melvill, J. C. &amp; Standen, R. (1907) The marine Mollusca of the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, 46, 119 - 157, 1 pl." type="journal article" year="1907">Melvill &amp; Standen (1907)</bibRefCitation>
only shows 2 spiral cords per whorl. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Strebel, H." box="[151,316,1207,1232]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63" pagination="1 - 112" refId="ref20010" refString="Strebel, H. (1908) Die Gastropoden (mit Ausnahme de nackten Opisthobranchier). Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der Schwedischen Sudpolar-Expedition 1901 - 1903, 6 (1), 1 - 112, pls. 1 - 6." type="journal article" year="1908">Strebel (1908)</bibRefCitation>
, who studied the same specimens, figured four spiral cords per whorl, a condition similar to that found in the material here examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
